The Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission (IEBC) has given Al Ghurair the green light to print ballot papers for the fresh presidential election.
 IEBC resolved to return to the Dubai-based firm after the National Treasury blocked its bid to procure the strategic materials through a UN development agency. 
 ALSO READ:

Daggers drawn as Uhuru, Raila battle to lock Western votes

 On Saturday, IEBC vice chairperson Connie Maina confirmed that Al Ghurair had received the printing order after Opposition and Jubilee failed to reach a consensus.
 “Both NASA and Jubilee have rejected the proposal. With limited options, the commission had to proceed in readiness for the October 26 elections. We are also running out of time. We are already in discussion with Al Ghurair to supply the ballot papers within the framework of the existing two-year contract,” Ms Maina said.
